# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: shellsort-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] It performs poorly in real-world use and is used primarily as an educational tool.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] More efficient algorithms such as quicksort, timsort, or merge sort are used by the sorting libraries built into popular programming languages such as Python and Java.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Bubble sort has a worst-case and average complexity of $O(n^{2})$ , where n is the number of items being sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Most practical sorting algorithms have substantially better worst-case or average complexity, often $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Even other $O(n^{2})$ sorting algorithms, such as insertion sort, generally run faster than bubble sort, and are no more complex.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For this reason, bubble sort is rarely used in practice.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Like insertion sort, bubble sort is adaptive, which can give it an advantage over algorithms like quicksort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] This means that it may outperform those algorithms in cases where the list is already mostly sorted (having a small number of inversions), despite the fact that it has worse average-case time complexity.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For example, bubble sort is $O(n)$ on a list that is already sorted, while quicksort would still perform its entire $O(n\log n)$ sorting process.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] While any sorting algorithm can be made $O(n)$ on a presorted list simply by checking the list before the algorithm runs, improved performance on almost-sorted lists is harder to replicate.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] The distance and direction that elements must move during the sort determine bubble sort's performance because elements move in different directions at different speeds.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] An element that must move toward the end of the list can move quickly because it can take part in successive swaps.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For example, the largest element in the list will win every swap, so it moves to its sorted position on the first pass even if it starts near the beginning.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] On the other hand, an element that must move toward the beginning of the list cannot move faster than one step per pass, so elements move toward the beginning very slowly.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] If the smallest element is at the end of the list, it will take $n-1$ passes to move it to the beginning.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] This has led to these types of elements being named rabbits and turtles, respectively, after the characters in Aesop's fable of The Tortoise and the Hare.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Various efforts have been made to eliminate turtles to improve the speed of bubble sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Cocktail sort is a bi-directional bubble sort that goes from beginning to end, and then reverses itself, going end to beginning.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] It can move turtles fairly well, but it retains $O(n^{2})$ worst-case complexity.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Comb sort compares elements separated by large gaps, and can move turtles extremely quickly before proceeding to smaller and smaller gaps to smooth out the list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Its average speed is comparable to faster algorithms like quicksort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Take an array of numbers "5 1 4 2 8", and sort the array from lowest number to greatest number using bubble sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] In each step, elements written in **bold** are being compared.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] 4 2 8 ), Here, algorithm compares the first two elements, and swaps since 5 > 1.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] ), Now, since these elements are already in order (8 > 5), algorithm does not swap them.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Now, the array is already sorted, but the algorithm does not know if it is completed.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] The algorithm needs one additional **whole** pass without **any** swap to know it is sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] The bubble sort algorithm can be optimized by observing that the *n*-th pass finds the *n*-th largest element and puts it into its final place.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] More generally, it can happen that more than one element is placed in its final position on a single pass.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] In particular, after every pass, all elements after the last swap are sorted, and do not need to be checked again.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Alternate modifications, such as the cocktail shaker sort attempt to improve on the bubble sort performance while keeping the same idea of repeatedly comparing and swapping adjacent items.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Although bubble sort is one of the simplest sorting algorithms to understand and implement, its *O*(*n*2) complexity means that its efficiency decreases dramatically on lists of more than a small number of elements.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Even among simple *O*(*n*2) sorting algorithms, algorithms like insertion sort are usually considerably more efficient.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Due to its simplicity, bubble sort is often used to introduce the concept of an algorithm, or a sorting algorithm, to introductory computer science students.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] However, some educators such as Owen Astrachan have gone to great lengths to disparage bubble sort and its continued popularity in computer science education, recommending that it no longer even be taught.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] The Jargon File, which famously calls bogosort "the archetypical [sic] perversely awful algorithm", also calls bubble sort "the generic bad algorithm".
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Donald Knuth, in *The Art of Computer Programming*, concluded that "the bubble sort seems to have nothing to recommend it, except a catchy name and the fact that it leads to some interesting theoretical problems", some of which he then discusses.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Bubble sort is asymptotically equivalent in running time to insertion sort in the worst case, but the two algorithms differ greatly in the number of swaps necessary.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Experimental results such as those of Astrachan have also shown that insertion sort performs considerably better even on random lists.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For these reasons, many modern algorithm textbooks avoid using the bubble sort algorithm in favor of insertion sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Bubble sort also interacts poorly with modern CPU hardware.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] It produces at least twice as many writes as insertion sort, twice as many cache misses, and asymptotically more branch mispredictions.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Experiments by Astrachan sorting strings in Java show bubble sort to be roughly one-fifth as fast as an insertion sort and 70% as fast as a selection sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] In computer graphics, bubble sort is popular for its capability to detect a very small error (like a swap of just two elements) in almost-sorted arrays and fix it with just linear complexity (2*n*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For example, it is used in a polygon filling algorithm, where bounding lines are sorted by their *x* coordinate at a specific scan line (a line parallel to the *x* axis), and with incrementing *y*, their order changes (two elements are swapped) only at intersections of two lines.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Bubble sort is a stable sort algorithm, like insertion sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] Bubble sort has been occasionally referred to as a "sinking sort".
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] For example, Donald Knuth describes the insertion of values at or towards their desired location as letting "[the value] settle to its proper level", and that "this method of sorting has sometimes been called the *sifting* or *sinking* technique.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/bubble-sort] The *smaller* values might be regarded as *lighter* and therefore be seen to progressively *bubble up* to the *top* of the list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A **comparison sort** is a type of sorting algorithm that only reads the list elements through a single abstract comparison operation (often a "less than or equal to" operator or a three-way comparison) that determines which of two elements should occur first in the final sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It is possible that both *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≤ *a* with *a* ≠ *b*; in this case either may come first in the sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In a stable sort, the input order determines the sorted order in this case.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts studied in the literature are "comparison-based".
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Elements *a* and *b* can be swapped or otherwise re-arranged by the algorithm only when the order between these elements has been established based on the outcomes of prior comparisons.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is the case when the order between *a* and *b* can be derived via the transitive closure of these prior comparison outcomes.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For comparison-based sorts, the decision to execute basic operations other than comparisons is based on the outcome of comparisons.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence in a time analysis, the number of executed comparisons is used to determine upper bound estimates for the number of executed basic operations such as swaps or assignments.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A metaphor for thinking about comparison sorts is that someone has a set of unlabelled weights and a balance scale.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Their goal is to line up the weights in order by their weight without any information except that obtained by placing two weights on the scale and seeing which one is heavier (or if they weigh the same).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] There are fundamental limits on the performance of comparison sorts.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A comparison sort must have an average-case lower bound of Ω(*n* log *n*) comparison operations, which is known as linearithmic time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is a consequence of the limited information available through comparisons alone — or, to put it differently, of the vague algebraic structure of totally ordered sets.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In this sense, mergesort, heapsort, and introsort are asymptotically optimal in terms of the number of comparisons they must perform, although this metric neglects other operations.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Non-comparison sorts (such as the examples discussed below) can achieve O(*n*) performance by using operations other than comparisons, allowing them to sidestep this lower bound (assuming elements are constant-sized).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts may run faster on some lists; many adaptive sorts such as insertion sort run in O(*n*) time on an already-sorted or nearly-sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Ω(*n* log *n*) lower bound applies only to the case in which the input list can be in any possible order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Despite these limitations, comparison sorts offer the notable practical advantage that control over the comparison function allows sorting of many different datatypes and fine control over how the list is sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts generally adapt more easily to complex orders such as the order of floating-point numbers.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Additionally, once a comparison function is written, any comparison sort can be used without modification; non-comparison sorts typically require specialized versions for each datatype.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This flexibility, together with the efficiency of the above comparison sorting algorithms on modern computers, has led to widespread preference for comparison sorts in most practical work.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Some sorting problems admit a strictly faster solution than the Ω(*n* log *n*) bound for comparison sorting by using non-comparison sorts; an example is integer sorting, where all keys are integers.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] When the keys form a small (compared to n) range, counting sort is an example algorithm that runs in linear time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Other integer sorting algorithms, such as radix sort, are not asymptotically faster than comparison sorting, but can be faster in practice.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The problem of sorting pairs of numbers by their sum is not subject to the Ω(*n*² log *n*) bound either (the square resulting from the pairing up); the best known algorithm still takes O(*n*² log *n*) time, but only O(*n*²) comparisons.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The number of comparisons that a comparison sort algorithm requires increases in proportion to $n\log(n)$ , where n is the number of elements to sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Given a list of distinct numbers (we can assume this because this is a worst-case analysis), there are n factorial permutations exactly one of which is the list in sorted order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The sort algorithm must gain enough information from the comparisons to identify the correct permutation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If the algorithm always completes after at most $f(n)$ steps, it cannot distinguish more than $2^{f(n)}$ cases because the keys are distinct and each comparison has only two possible outcomes.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This provides the lower-bound part of the claim.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A more precise bound can be given via Stirling's approximation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An upper bound of the same form, with the same leading term as the bound obtained from Stirling's approximation, follows from the existence of the algorithms that attain this bound in the worst case, like merge sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The above argument provides an *absolute*, rather than only asymptotic lower bound on the number of comparisons, namely $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n!)\right\rceil$ comparisons.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This lower bound is fairly good (it can be approached within a linear tolerance by a simple merge sort), but it is known to be inexact.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, $\left\lceil \log _{2}(13!)\right\rceil =33$ , but the minimal number of comparisons to sort 13 elements has been proved to be 34.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Determining the *exact* number of comparisons needed to sort a given number of entries is a computationally hard problem even for small *n*, and no simple formula for the solution is known.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For some of the few concrete values that have been computed, see OEIS: A036604.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A similar bound applies to the average number of comparisons.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] it is impossible to determine which order the input is in with fewer than log2(*n*!) comparisons on average.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This can be most easily seen using concepts from information theory.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Shannon entropy of such a random permutation is log2(*n*!) bits.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Since a comparison can give only two results, the maximum amount of information it provides is 1 bit.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Therefore, after *k* comparisons the remaining entropy of the permutation, given the results of those comparisons, is at least log2(*n*!) − *k* bits on average.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To perform the sort, complete information is needed, so the remaining entropy must be 0.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It follows that *k* must be at least log2(*n*!) on average.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The lower bound derived via information theory is phrased as 'information-theoretic lower bound'.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The information-theoretic lower bound is correct, but may be far from the strongest possible lower bound.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, the information-theoretic lower bound of selection is $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n)\right\rceil$ whereas $n-1$ comparisons are needed by an adversarial argument.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The interplay between information-theoretic lower bound and the true lower bound are much like a real-valued function lower-bounding an integer function.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] However, this is not exactly correct when the average case is considered.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To unearth what happens while analyzing the average case, the key is that what does 'average' refer to?
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] With some knowledge of information theory, the information-theoretic lower bound averages over the set of all permutations as a whole.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] But any computer algorithms (under what are believed currently) must treat each permutation as an individual instance of the problem.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence, the average lower bound we're searching for is averaged over all individual cases.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To search for the lower bound relating to the non-achievability of computers, we adopt the Decision tree model.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Let's rephrase a bit of what our objective is.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the Decision tree model, the lower bound to be shown is the lower bound of the average length of root-to-leaf paths of an $n!$ -leaf binary tree (in which each leaf corresponds to a permutation).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The minimum average length of a binary tree with a given number of leaves is achieved by a balanced full binary tree, because any other binary tree can have its path length reduced by moving a pair of leaves to a higher position.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, for *n* = 3, the information-theoretic lower bound for the average case is approximately 2.58, while the average lower bound derived via Decision tree model is 8/3, approximately 2.67.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the case that multiple items may have the same key, there is no obvious statistical interpretation for the term "average case", so an argument like the above cannot be applied without making specific assumptions about the distribution of keys.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Can easy compute for real algorithm sorted-list-merging (array are sorted n-blocks with size 1, merge to 1–1 to 2, merge 2–2 to 4...).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If a list is already close to sorted, according to some measure of sortedness, the number of comparisons required to sort it can be smaller.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An adaptive sort takes advantage of this "presortedness" and runs more quickly on nearly-sorted inputs, often while still maintaining an $O(n\log n)$ worst case time bound.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An example is adaptive heap sort, a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It takes time $O(n\log k)$ , where k is the average, over all values x in the sequence, of the number of times the sequence jumps from below x to above x or vice versa.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computer science, an **in-place algorithm** is an algorithm that operates directly on the input data structure without requiring extra space proportional to the input size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In other words, it modifies the input in place, without creating a separate copy of the data structure.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm which is not in-place is sometimes called **not-in-place** or **out-of-place**.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In-place can have slightly different meanings.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In its strictest form, the algorithm can only have a constant amount of extra space, counting everything including function calls and pointers.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, this form is very limited as simply having an index to a length *n* array requires *O*(log *n*) bits.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] More broadly, in-place means that the algorithm does not use extra space for manipulating the input but may require a small though non-constant extra space for its operation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Usually, this space is *O*(log *n*), though sometimes anything in *o*(*n*) is allowed.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that space complexity also has varied choices in whether or not to count the index lengths as part of the space used.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Often, the space complexity is given in terms of the number of indices or pointers needed, ignoring their length.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In this article, we refer to total space complexity (DSPACE), counting pointer lengths.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Therefore, the space requirements here have an extra log *n* factor compared to an analysis that ignores the lengths of indices and pointers.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm may or may not count the output as part of its space usage.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since in-place algorithms usually overwrite their input with output, no additional space is needed.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] When writing the output to write-only memory or a stream, it may be more appropriate to only consider the working space of the algorithm.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In theoretical applications such as log-space reductions, it is more typical to always ignore output space (in these cases it is more essential that the output is *write-only*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Given an array `a` of *n* items, suppose we want an array that holds the same elements in reversed order and to dispose of the original.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] One seemingly simple way to do this is to create a new array of equal size, fill it with copies from `a` in the appropriate order and then delete `a`.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Unfortunately, this requires *O*(*n*) extra space for having the arrays `a` and `b` available simultaneously.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Also, allocation and deallocation are often slow operations.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since we no longer need `a`, we can instead overwrite it with its own reversal using this in-place algorithm which will only need constant number (2) of integers for the auxiliary variables `i` and `tmp`, no matter how large the array is.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] As another example, many sorting algorithms rearrange arrays into sorted order in-place, including: bubble sort, comb sort, selection sort, insertion sort, heapsort, and Shell sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] These algorithms require only a few pointers, so their space complexity is *O*(log *n*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Quicksort operates in-place on the data to be sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, quicksort requires *O*(log *n*) stack space pointers to keep track of the subarrays in its divide and conquer strategy.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Consequently, quicksort needs *O*(log2 *n*) additional space.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Although this non-constant space technically takes quicksort out of the in-place category, quicksort and other algorithms needing only *O*(log *n*) additional pointers are usually considered in-place algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Most selection algorithms are also in-place, although some considerably rearrange the input array in the process of finding the final, constant-sized result.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Some text manipulation algorithms such as trim and reverse may be done in-place.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computational complexity theory, the strict definition of in-place algorithms includes all algorithms with *O*(1) space complexity, the class **DSPACE**(1).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is very limited; it equals the regular languages.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In fact, it does not even include any of the examples listed above.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Algorithms are usually considered in L, the class of problems requiring *O*(log *n*) additional space, to be in-place.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is more in line with the practical definition, as it allows numbers of size *n* as pointers or indices.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This expanded definition still excludes quicksort, however, because of its recursive calls.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This in turn yields in-place algorithms for problems such as determining if a graph is bipartite or testing whether two graphs have the same number of connected components.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In many cases, the space requirements of an algorithm can be drastically cut by using a randomized algorithm.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] For example, if one wishes to know if two vertices in a graph of *n* vertices are in the same connected component of the graph, there is no known simple, deterministic, in-place algorithm to determine this.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, if we simply start at one vertex and perform a random walk of about 20*n*3 steps, the chance that we will stumble across the other vertex provided that it is in the same component is very high.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Similarly, there are simple randomized in-place algorithms for primality testing such as the Miller–Rabin primality test, and there are also simple in-place randomized factoring algorithms such as Pollard's rho algorithm.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Functional programming languages often discourage or do not support explicit in-place algorithms that overwrite data, since this is a type of side effect; instead, they only allow new data to be constructed.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, good functional language compilers will often recognize when an object very similar to an existing one is created and then the old one is thrown away, and will optimize this into a simple mutation "under the hood".
[src:shellsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that it is possible in principle to carefully construct in-place algorithms that do not modify data (unless the data is no longer being used), but this is rarely done in practice.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When people manually sort cards in a bridge hand, most use a method that is similar to insertion sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Insertion sort iterates, consuming one input element each repetition, and grows a sorted output list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] At each iteration, insertion sort removes one element from the input data, finds the correct location within the sorted list, and inserts it there.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It repeats until no input elements remain.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Sorting is typically done in-place, by iterating up the array, growing the sorted list behind it.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] At each array-position, it checks the value there against the largest value in the sorted list (which happens to be next to it, in the previous array-position checked).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If larger, it leaves the element in place and moves to the next.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If smaller, it finds the correct position within the sorted list, shifts all the larger values up to make a space, and inserts into that correct position.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The resulting array after *k* iterations has the property where the first *k* + 1 entries are sorted ("+1" because the first entry is skipped).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] with each element greater than *x* copied to the right as it is compared against *x*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] To perform an insertion sort, begin at the left-most element of the array and invoke *Insert* to insert each element encountered into its correct position.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The ordered sequence into which the element is inserted is stored at the beginning of the array in the set of indices already examined.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Each insertion overwrites a single value: the value being inserted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The outer loop runs over all the elements except the first one, because the single-element prefix `A[0:1]` is trivially sorted, so the invariant that the first `i` entries are sorted is true from the start.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The inner loop moves element `A[i]` to its correct place so that after the loop, the first `i+1` elements are sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Note that the `**and**`-operator in the test must use short-circuit evaluation, otherwise the test might result in an array bounds error, when `j=0` and it tries to evaluate `A[j-1] > A[j]` (i.e. accessing `A[-1]` fails).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The new inner loop shifts elements to the right to clear a spot for `x = A[i]`.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm can also be implemented in a recursive way.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The initial call would be *`insertionSortR(A, length(A)-1)`*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It does not make the code any shorter, it also does not reduce the execution time, but it increases the additional memory consumption from O(1) to O(N) (at the deepest level of recursion the stack contains N references to the `A` array, each with accompanying value of variable `n` from N down to 1).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The best case input is an array that is already sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In this case insertion sort has a linear running time (i.e., O(*n*)).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] During each iteration, the first remaining element of the input is only compared with the right-most element of the sorted subsection of the array.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The simplest worst case input is an array sorted in reverse order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The set of all worst case inputs consists of all arrays where each element is the smallest or second-smallest of the elements before it.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In these cases every iteration of the inner loop will scan and shift the entire sorted subsection of the array before inserting the next element.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] This gives insertion sort a quadratic running time (i.e., O(*n*2)).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The average case is also quadratic, which makes insertion sort impractical for sorting large arrays.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Example: The following table shows the steps for sorting the sequence {3, 7, 4, 9, 5, 2, 6, 1}.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In each step, the key under consideration is underlined.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The key that was moved (or left in place because it was the biggest yet considered) in the previous step is marked with an asterisk.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Insertion sort is very similar to selection sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] As in selection sort, after *k* passes through the array, the first *k* elements are in sorted order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] However, the fundamental difference between the two algorithms is that insertion sort scans backwards from the current key, while selection sort scans forwards.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] This results in selection sort making the first k elements the *k* smallest elements of the unsorted input, while in insertion sort they are simply the first *k* elements of the input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] On average (assuming the rank of the (*k* + 1)-st element rank is random), insertion sort will require comparing and shifting half of the previous *k* elements, meaning that insertion sort will perform about half as many comparisons as selection sort on average.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In the worst case for insertion sort (when the input array is reverse-sorted), insertion sort performs just as many comparisons as selection sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In general, insertion sort will write to the array O(*n*2) times, whereas selection sort will write only O(n) times.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] For this reason selection sort may be preferable in cases where writing to memory is significantly more expensive than reading, such as with EEPROM or flash memory.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Therefore, a useful optimization in the implementation of those algorithms is a hybrid approach, using the simpler algorithm when the array has been divided to a small size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Shell made substantial improvements to the algorithm; the modified version is called Shell sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The sorting algorithm compares elements separated by a distance that decreases on each pass.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Shell sort has distinctly improved running times in practical work, with two simple variants requiring O(*n*3/2) and O(*n*4/3) running time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If the cost of comparisons exceeds the cost of swaps, as is the case for example with string keys stored by reference or with human interaction (such as choosing one of a pair displayed side-by-side), then using *binary insertion sort* may yield better performance.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Binary insertion sort employs a binary search to determine the correct location to insert new elements, and therefore performs ⌈log2 *n*⌉ comparisons in the worst case.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When each element in the array is searched for and inserted this is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm as a whole still has a running time of O(*n*2) on average because of the series of swaps required for each insertion.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The number of swaps can be reduced by calculating the position of multiple elements before moving them.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] For example, if the target position of two elements is calculated before they are moved into the proper position, the number of swaps can be reduced by about 25% for random data.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In the extreme case, this variant works similar to merge sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] A variant named *binary merge sort* uses a *binary insertion sort* to sort groups of 32 elements, followed by a final sort using merge sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] It combines the speed of insertion sort on small data sets with the speed of merge sort on large data sets.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] To avoid having to make a series of swaps for each insertion, the input could be stored in a linked list, which allows elements to be spliced into or out of the list in constant time when the position in the list is known.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] However, searching a linked list requires sequentially following the links from each element to the next (or previous) element: a linked list does not have random access, so it cannot use a faster method such as binary search to find the insertion point for an unsorted element.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] Therefore, the running time required for searching is O(*n*), and the time for sorting is O(*n*2).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If a more sophisticated data structure (e.g., heap or binary tree) is used, the time required for searching and insertion can be reduced significantly; this is the essence of heap sort and binary tree sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] In 2006 Bender, Martin Farach-Colton, and Mosteiro published a new variant of insertion sort called *library sort* or *gapped insertion sort* that leaves a small number of unused spaces (i.e., "gaps") spread throughout the array.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The benefit is that insertions need only shift elements over until a gap is reached.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The authors show that this sorting algorithm runs with high probability in O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If a skip list is used, the insertion time is brought down to O(log *n*), and swaps are not needed because the skip list is implemented on a linked list structure.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The final running time for insertion would be O(*n* log *n*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] If the items are stored in a linked list, then the list can be sorted with O(1) additional space.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm starts with an initially empty (and therefore trivially sorted) list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The input items are taken off the list one at a time, and then inserted in the proper place in the sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] When the input list is empty, the sorted list has the desired result.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] The algorithm below uses a trailing pointer for the insertion into the sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/insertion-sort] A simpler recursive method rebuilds the list each time (rather than splicing) and can use O(*n*) stack space.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The algorithm was first published by Donald Shell in 1959, and has nothing to do with shells.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Shellsort is an optimization of insertion sort that allows the exchange of items that are far apart.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The idea is to arrange the list of elements so that, starting anywhere, taking every *h*th element produces a sorted list.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] It can also be thought of as *h* interleaved lists, each individually sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Beginning with large values of *h* allows elements to move long distances in the original list, reducing large amounts of disorder quickly, and leaving less work for smaller *h*-sort steps to do.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] If the list is then *k-sorted* for some smaller integer *k*, then the list remains *h*-sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] A final sort with *h* = 1 ensures the list is fully sorted at the end, but a judiciously chosen decreasing sequence of *h* values leaves very little work for this final pass to do.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] In simplistic terms, this means if we have an array of 1024 numbers, our first gap (*h*) could be 512.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] We then run through the list comparing each element in the first half to the element in the second half.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Our second gap (*k*) is 256, which breaks the array into four sections (starting at 0, 256, 512, 768), and we make sure the first items in each section are sorted relative to each other, then the second item in each section, and so on.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] In practice the gap sequence could be anything, but the last gap is always 1 to finish the sort (effectively finishing with an ordinary insertion sort).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] An example run of Shellsort with gaps 5, 3 and 1 is shown below.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The last pass, 1-sorting, is an ordinary insertion sort of the entire array (*a*1,..., *a*12).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] As the example illustrates, the subarrays that Shellsort operates on are initially short; later they are longer but almost ordered.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] In both cases insertion sort works efficiently.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Unlike insertion sort, Shellsort is not a stable sort since gapped insertions transport equal elements past one another and thus lose their original order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] It is an adaptive sorting algorithm in that it executes faster when the input is partially sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] This is a C# example using Marcin Ciura's gap sequence, with an inner insertion sort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The question of deciding which gap sequence to use is difficult.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Every gap sequence that contains 1 yields a correct sort (as this makes the final pass an ordinary insertion sort); however, the properties of thus obtained versions of Shellsort may be very different.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Too few gaps slows down the passes, and too many gaps produces an overhead.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The table below compares most proposed gap sequences published so far.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Some of them have decreasing elements that depend on the size of the sorted array (*N*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Others are increasing infinite sequences, whose elements less than *N* should be used in reverse order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] When the binary representation of *N* contains many consecutive zeroes, Shellsort using Shell's original gap sequence makes Θ(*N*2) comparisons in the worst case.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] For instance, this case occurs for *N* equal to a power of two when elements greater and smaller than the median occupy odd and even positions respectively, since they are compared only in the last pass.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The Gonnet and Baeza-Yates implementation of Shellsort (GBY91) also uses gaps that start with *N* and performs better than many of the other sequences on average, but is also prone to a Θ(*N*2) worst case: Let X be a gap in the sequence.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The GBY91 gaps' common ratio of 2.2 permits at least two consecutive integers Y and Y+1 to equal X from floor division by 2.2.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Choose Y or Y+1, whichever one is even, to repeat the process, and one obtains an infinitely long chain of even gaps > X by induction.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] With X = 1, one generates infinite options for *N* where all GBY91 gaps > 1 are even and thus are Θ(*N*2) on the same aforementioned worst case input for Shell's original gaps.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Although it has higher complexity than the *O*(*N* log *N*) that is optimal for comparison sorts, Pratt's version lends itself to sorting networks and has the same asymptotic gate complexity as Batcher's bitonic sorter.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Gonnet and Baeza-Yates observed that Shellsort makes the fewest comparisons on average when the ratios of successive gaps are roughly equal to 2.2.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] This is why their sequence with ratio 2.2 and Tokuda's sequence with ratio 2.25 prove efficient.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] However, it is not known why this is so.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Sedgewick recommends using gaps which have low greatest common divisors or are pairwise coprime.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Using gaps which are odd numbers appears to help - speedups of about 25% have been seen in practice versus Shell's original code.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Using gaps which are not multiples of 2, 3 or 5 appear to reduce run times further - speedups of about 35% versus Shell's original seem possible.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Using gaps which are prime numbers only (ending with 1), appear to produce speedups of about 40% over the original code.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] With respect to the average number of comparisons, Ciura's sequence has the best known performance; gaps greater than 701 were not determined but the sequence can be further extended according to the recursive formula $h_{k}=\lfloor 2.25h_{k-1}\rfloor$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Tokuda's sequence, defined by the simple formula $h_{k}=\lceil h'_{k}\rceil$ , where $h'_{k}=2.25h'_{k-1}+1$ , $h'_{1}=1$ , can be recommended for practical applications.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] If the maximum input size is small, as may occur if Shellsort is used on small subarrays by another recursive sorting algorithm such as quicksort or merge sort, then it is possible to tabulate an optimal sequence for each input size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The following property holds: after *h*2-sorting of any *h*1-sorted array, the array remains *h*1-sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Every *h*1-sorted and *h*2-sorted array is also (*a*1*h*1+*a*2*h*2)-sorted, for any nonnegative integers *a*1 and *a*2.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The worst-case complexity of Shellsort is therefore connected with the Frobenius problem: for given integers *h*1,..., *hn* with gcd = 1, the Frobenius number *g*(*h*1,..., *hn*) is the greatest integer that cannot be represented as *a*1*h*1+ ... +*anhn* with nonnegative integer *a*1,..., *an*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Using known formulae for Frobenius numbers, we can determine the worst-case complexity of Shellsort for several classes of gap sequences.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Proven results are shown in the above table.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Mark Allen Weiss proved that Shellsort runs in *O*(*N* log *N*) time when the input array is in reverse order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] With respect to the average number of operations, none of the proven results concerns a practical gap sequence.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Knuth determined the average complexity of sorting an *N*-element array with two gaps (*h*, 1) to be ${\frac {2N^{2}}{h}}+{\sqrt {\pi N^{3}h}}$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] It follows that a two-pass Shellsort with *h* = Θ(*N*1/3) makes on average *O*(*N*5/3) comparisons/inversions/running time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Yao found the average complexity of a three-pass Shellsort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Based on experiments, it is conjectured that Shellsort with Hibbard's gap sequence runs in *O*(*N*5/4) average time, and that Gonnet and Baeza-Yates's sequence requires on average 0.41*N* ln *N* (ln ln *N* + 1/6) element moves.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Approximations of the average number of operations formerly put forward for other sequences fail when sorted arrays contain millions of elements.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The graph below shows the average number of element comparisons use by various gap sequences, divided by the theoretical lower bound, i.e. log2*N*!.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Applying the theory of Kolmogorov complexity, Jiang, Li, and Vitányi proved the following lower bound for the order of the average number of operations/running time in a *p*-pass Shellsort: Ω(*pN*1+1/*p*) when *p* ≤ log2*N* and Ω(*pN*) when *p* > log2*N*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Therefore, Shellsort has prospects of running in an average time that asymptotically grows like *N* log*N* only when using gap sequences whose number of gaps grows in proportion to the logarithm of the array size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] It is, however, unknown whether Shellsort can reach this asymptotic order of average-case complexity, which is optimal for comparison sorts.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The lower bound was improved by Vitányi for every number of passes p to $\Omega (N\sum _{k=1}^{p}h_{k-1}/h_{k})$ where $h_{0}=N$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] This result implies for example the Jiang-Li-Vitányi lower bound for all p -pass increment sequences and improves that lower bound for particular increment sequences.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] In fact all bounds (lower and upper) currently known for the average case are precisely matched by this lower bound.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] For example, this gives the new result that the Janson-Knuth upper bound is matched by the resulting lower bound for the used increment sequence, showing that three pass Shellsort for this increment sequence uses $\Theta (N^{23/15})$ comparisons/inversions/running time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] The worst-case complexity of any version of Shellsort is of higher order: Plaxton, Poonen, and Suel showed that it grows at least as rapidly as $\Omega \left(N\left({\log N \over \log \log N}\right)^{2}\right)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Robert Cypher proved a stronger lower bound: $\Omega \left(N{{(\log N)^{2}} \over {\log \log N}}\right)$ when $h_{s+1}>h_{s}$ for all s .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Shellsort performs more operations and has higher cache miss ratio than quicksort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] However, since it can be implemented using little code and does not use the call stack, some implementations of the qsort function in the C standard library targeted at embedded systems use it instead of quicksort.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Shellsort is, for example, used in the uClibc library.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] For similar reasons, in the past, Shellsort was used in the Linux kernel.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] Shellsort can also serve as a sub-algorithm of introspective sort, to sort short subarrays and to prevent a slowdown when the recursion depth exceeds a given limit.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/shellsort] This principle is employed, for instance, in the bzip2 compressor.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:shellsort-algorithm/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
